00:25:23.525 --> 00:25:24.025
Yes.

00:25:24.025 --> 00:25:25.456
AUDIENCE: Who created Chainmail?

00:25:27.830 --> 00:25:29.080
MICHAEL WITWER: Good question.

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:34.880
So the easy answer is Gary
Gygax created Chainmail.

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:37.882
Chainmail was a
miniatures game that

00:25:37.882 --> 00:25:40.340
was published about four years
before Dungeons and Dragons.

00:25:40.340 --> 00:25:43.470
As I mentioned,
before D&amp;D came out,

00:25:43.470 --> 00:25:45.720
there was a lot of
different types of gaming.

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:47.750
And they were all disparate
factions of gaming.

00:25:47.750 --> 00:25:50.240
You had miniatures over here,
you had wargaming over here.

00:25:50.240 --> 00:25:54.500
Wargaming was, basically, think
of hex max maps and cardboard

00:25:54.500 --> 00:25:56.060
contras or pogs.

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:58.160
And then you've got diplomacy
in the middle, which

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:00.260
is kind of this game
where you could play it

00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:01.840
a few different ways--
you can play it by mail--

00:26:01.840 --> 00:26:04.298
but it's a game where there's
a certain amount of character

00:26:04.298 --> 00:26:04.910
assumption.

00:26:04.910 --> 00:26:07.260
And you play the game
through negotiation and guile

00:26:07.260 --> 00:26:07.960
and other means.

00:26:07.960 --> 00:26:09.637
So it's a very
different type of game.

00:26:09.637 --> 00:26:11.470
And you could argue,
again, that these three

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:14.090
disparate components
make up the elements that

00:26:14.090 --> 00:26:15.830
become a role-playing game.

00:26:15.830 --> 00:26:21.070
So Gary Gygax had founded
this local gaming group

00:26:21.070 --> 00:26:23.800
in Lake Geneva and they
used to play miniatures

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:27.119
on his sand table that he
had built in his basement.

00:26:27.119 --> 00:26:28.660
And they came up
with these, kind of,

00:26:28.660 --> 00:26:32.395
homebrew rules about, basically,
the mechanics of how one

00:26:32.395 --> 00:26:33.779
would play minutures wargames.

00:26:33.779 --> 00:26:35.070
There's a lot of ways to do it.

00:26:35.070 --> 00:26:37.080
Some people use rulers
and measurements,

00:26:37.080 --> 00:26:38.950
there's just a lot of ways.

00:26:38.950 --> 00:26:42.420
And Gary had teamed up with a
fellow named Jeff Perren, who

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:44.300
was a member of his
local gaming group,

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:46.920
and had started to
refine miniatures rules

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:49.720
for their homebrew game.

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:53.640
And that became a rule
set known as Chainmail,

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:55.810
published by Guidon Games.

00:26:55.810 --> 00:26:58.400
Chainmail had a
lot of the classes,

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:01.520
and a lot of even
the combat mechanics

00:27:01.520 --> 00:27:04.820
that one would recognize
in Dungeons and Dragons.

00:27:04.820 --> 00:27:07.410
And so you could say Chainmail
was an important predecessor

00:27:07.410 --> 00:27:08.230
piece.

00:27:08.230 --> 00:27:10.530
And, in fact, it was
this game, Chainmail,

00:27:10.530 --> 00:27:13.345
that became a major
inspiration to Dave Arneson

00:27:13.345 --> 00:27:15.470
when he was rolling out a
game he called Blackmoor.

00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:18.250
Dave Arneson was
playing what most of us

00:27:18.250 --> 00:27:20.635
would recognize as the
first role-playing game

00:27:20.635 --> 00:27:23.010
or something that at least
resembles a role-playing game,

00:27:23.010 --> 00:27:24.920
with his Minneapolis
gaming group.

00:27:24.920 --> 00:27:25.890
He called it Blackmoor.

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:28.556
He would use the Chainmail
rules for his combat.

00:27:28.556 --> 00:27:30.430
And he would use some
of these other concepts

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:32.046
he had gotten through
diplomacy, and

00:27:32.046 --> 00:27:34.045
through some other concepts,
that he had come up

00:27:34.045 --> 00:27:37.770
in the Minneapolis gaming group
for this kind of role-playing

00:27:37.770 --> 00:27:38.720
game called Blackmoor.

00:27:38.720 --> 00:27:42.230
This is a game he showed to
Gary in 1972-- demonstrated,

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:44.410
I should say, for Gary in 1972.

00:27:44.410 --> 00:27:46.630
That's when those two really
got together and start

00:27:46.630 --> 00:27:52.130
working on what has become
Dungeons and Dragons.

00:27:52.130 --> 00:27:52.634
Yes.

00:27:52.634 --> 00:27:56.094
AUDIENCE: Did you ever chance
to speak with his first wife?

00:27:56.094 --> 00:27:58.010
MICHAEL WITWER: I spoke
quite a lot with Mary.

00:27:58.010 --> 00:27:58.650
Mary Jo.

00:27:58.650 --> 00:28:00.066
AUDIENCE: So what
was her thinking

00:28:00.066 --> 00:28:02.614
of having a husband who spends
his nights doing this stuff

00:28:02.614 --> 00:28:03.780
with five kids and all that?

00:28:03.780 --> 00:28:05.196
MICHAEL WITWER:
It didn't go well.

00:28:05.196 --> 00:28:05.776
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:05.776 --> 00:28:07.400
You had mentioned,
it's his first wife.

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:10.990
There's a reason why
it was his first wife.

00:28:10.990 --> 00:28:12.776
So one really
important thing to me.

00:28:12.776 --> 00:28:15.234
I had mentioned that is was
really important that this book

00:28:15.234 --> 00:28:16.140
be comprehensive.

00:28:16.140 --> 00:28:18.790
I don't mean it covers every
fact and detail of Gary life.

00:28:18.790 --> 00:28:22.209
Rather that I cover
every area of his life.

00:28:22.209 --> 00:28:23.750
And one really
important part to that

00:28:23.750 --> 00:28:25.627
was can I find somebody
that's was there

00:28:25.627 --> 00:28:26.710
at every part of his life.

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:28.781
That was really
important because I

00:28:28.781 --> 00:28:30.780
write the book in a
narrative, nonfiction style,

00:28:30.780 --> 00:28:33.776
there is an oral history
element about the whole thing.

00:28:33.776 --> 00:28:35.150
I wanted to get
into Gary's head.

00:28:35.150 --> 00:28:39.070
And I wanted to be beyond
facts and figures, per se.

00:28:39.070 --> 00:28:40.610
And so the question
is, could I get

00:28:40.610 --> 00:28:42.330
to people that knew Gary
at every different part

00:28:42.330 --> 00:28:42.830
of his life?

00:28:42.830 --> 00:28:45.980
And the good news was not
only was Mary accessible--

00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:49.190
and I spent a lot
of time with her--

00:28:49.190 --> 00:28:51.820
but she knew Gary since
he was five years old.

00:28:51.820 --> 00:28:54.302
They met in Lake Geneva when
they were five years old.

00:28:54.302 --> 00:28:55.760
And so, all of a
sudden, I actually

00:28:55.760 --> 00:28:57.384
had somebody that
knew Gary through all

00:28:57.384 --> 00:28:59.190
these critical parts
of his early life,

00:28:59.190 --> 00:29:02.180
that frankly, there's nobody
else there to talk about them.

00:29:02.180 --> 00:29:04.070
Everyone else's is
either deceased--

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:05.910
And, of course, Gary writes a
lot about these things as well.

00:29:05.910 --> 00:29:07.868
So you can, kind of, fill
in a lot of the gaps.

00:29:07.868 --> 00:29:09.900
But I worked quite
a lot with Mary Jo.

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:11.850
And to answer your question.

00:29:11.850 --> 00:29:14.827
So they had a very tumultuous
relationship, extremely.

00:29:14.827 --> 00:29:16.410
And there's a lot
of reasons for that.

00:29:16.410 --> 00:29:19.400
I mean, for one thing, Gary
was obsessed with hobbies.

00:29:19.400 --> 00:29:22.370
Namely gaming but
a lot of things.

00:29:22.370 --> 00:29:23.537
Gary was just that type.

00:29:23.537 --> 00:29:25.495
He was your classic, kind
of, eccentric genius.

00:29:25.495 --> 00:29:27.260
He just was.

00:29:27.260 --> 00:29:30.196
He could not turn the spout off
of ideas that were rolling out

00:29:30.196 --> 00:29:31.740
of him all the time.

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:33.550
And that was very hard
on their marriage.

00:29:33.550 --> 00:29:35.426
This is a guy that would
come home many days.

00:29:35.426 --> 00:29:37.008
after an hour and a
half on the train,

00:29:37.008 --> 00:29:38.740
working as an
insurance underwriter.

00:29:38.740 --> 00:29:40.490
He would sit down, he
might read his mail.

00:29:40.490 --> 00:29:42.865
He might see whatever
diplomacy play-by-mail game

00:29:42.865 --> 00:29:45.480
he was playing at the time.

00:29:45.480 --> 00:29:46.450
See his kids briefly.

00:29:46.450 --> 00:29:47.950
And he would retire
to his den where

00:29:47.950 --> 00:29:51.950
he'd be writing on his next
game or his next gaming variant.

00:29:51.950 --> 00:29:54.396
And the thing that was
striking about Gary,

00:29:54.396 --> 00:29:56.850
when you looked at his
early life especially,

00:29:56.850 --> 00:29:59.610
is the amount of production this
guy was able to keep up with.

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:02.634
Knowing that he had a
family and a full time job.

00:30:02.634 --> 00:30:04.050
When you see how
much writing he's

00:30:04.050 --> 00:30:05.383
doing in these various fanzines.

00:30:05.383 --> 00:30:07.660
Fanzines are basically
early gaming newsletters,

00:30:07.660 --> 00:30:10.330
for lack of a better term,
that these gaming groups would,

00:30:10.330 --> 00:30:11.900
kind of, coordinate through.

00:30:11.900 --> 00:30:14.670
And Gary's contributing to
these things on a monthly basis.

00:30:14.670 --> 00:30:17.000
New gaming variants, new
letters, you name it.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:20.582
He's constantly cranking out
material, he can't turn it off.

00:30:20.582 --> 00:30:22.540
And, of course, that's
very hard on a marriage,

00:30:22.540 --> 00:30:24.581
especially one that has
so many responsibilities.

00:30:24.581 --> 00:30:27.800
And of course, meanwhile, they
don't have a lot of money.

00:30:27.800 --> 00:30:31.234
They're struggling and when
Gary loses his job in 1970, when

00:30:31.234 --> 00:30:33.025
Mary Jo is eight and
a half months pregnant

00:30:33.025 --> 00:30:34.452
with her fifth child.

00:30:34.452 --> 00:30:36.910
One can imagine this was quite
a strain on the relationship

00:30:36.910 --> 00:30:38.610
also.

00:30:38.610 --> 00:30:40.586
So, again, that's
something that I

00:30:40.586 --> 00:30:42.410
think is very worth
reading in the book

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:45.382
just because it's such a
tumultuous relationship.

00:30:45.382 --> 00:30:46.590
And a wonderful relationship.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:48.131
It bore some really
wonderful things.

00:30:48.131 --> 00:30:51.920
But by 1983, they were
ships passing in the night

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:56.020
and the love, kind
of, started to fade.

00:30:56.020 --> 00:30:56.580
Yes.

00:30:56.580 --> 00:31:00.134
SAGE: So there's been a number
of great books on the history

00:31:00.134 --> 00:31:02.050
of Dungeons and Dragons
and role-playing games

00:31:02.050 --> 00:31:03.610
the last few years.

00:31:03.610 --> 00:31:06.320
Why do you think that now all
of these books are happening?

00:31:06.320 --> 00:31:07.651
MICHAEL WITWER: Hmm.

00:31:07.651 --> 00:31:08.650
That's a great question.

00:31:08.650 --> 00:31:12.670
I mean, I think it comes
back, to a certain extent,

00:31:12.670 --> 00:31:15.110
that the people who grew
up playing these games

00:31:15.110 --> 00:31:18.457
are the ones that are the
most relevant in our society.

00:31:18.457 --> 00:31:20.040
Oh, I shouldn't say
the most relevant.

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:21.180
That's an unfair thing to say.

00:31:21.180 --> 00:31:23.060
Just that a lot of these
people have really become

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:24.310
the masters of the generation.

00:31:24.310 --> 00:31:25.750
I mean, take John Favreau.

00:31:25.750 --> 00:31:27.660
As a director, he
talks about D&amp;D

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:29.476
taught him to be a storyteller.

00:31:29.476 --> 00:31:31.350
Junot Diaz, the Pulitzer
Prize-winning author

00:31:31.350 --> 00:31:34.020
of "The Brief Wondrous
Life of Oscar Wao,"

00:31:34.020 --> 00:31:37.130
says that D&amp;D was my
apprenticeship in storytelling.

00:31:37.130 --> 00:31:39.570
Sam Lipsyte says that I
became a writer because I

00:31:39.570 --> 00:31:40.900
couldn't be a Dungeon Master.

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:43.810
I wanted to be a Dungeon Master,
I wanted to control the story.

00:31:43.810 --> 00:31:45.730
And the list goes
on and on and on.

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:48.300
Whether it be Steve
Colbert or Anderson Cooper.

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:50.980
A lot of these people that are
out there doing amazing things

00:31:50.980 --> 00:31:52.127
found a lot of their
roots, and a lot

00:31:52.127 --> 00:31:54.252
of their early creativity,
in Dungeons and Dragons.

00:31:54.252 --> 00:31:55.840
So, I think, now
is the time where

00:31:55.840 --> 00:31:57.548
there's a confluence
of all those things.

00:31:57.548 --> 00:32:00.010
And I think people that were
early computer programmers

00:32:00.010 --> 00:32:02.500
are starting to realize, wow,
I got a lot of these concepts

00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:03.251
from the tabletop.

00:32:03.251 --> 00:32:05.583
And, of course, they're showing
up on people's browsers.

00:32:05.583 --> 00:32:08.250
And people that didn't grow up
playing Dungeons and Dragons,

00:32:08.250 --> 00:32:10.333
or another role-playing
game, wouldn't necessarily

00:32:10.333 --> 00:32:11.830
recognize that
these are concepts

00:32:11.830 --> 00:32:14.430
that used to be unique
to a role-playing game.

00:32:14.430 --> 00:32:16.590
So I think, to a
certain extent, I

00:32:16.590 --> 00:32:20.600
guess the easy answer is
that we live in a time

00:32:20.600 --> 00:32:22.616
when it is geek to be chic.

00:32:22.616 --> 00:32:24.240
Or, it is chic to be
geek, to be exact.

00:32:24.240 --> 00:32:24.990
Not geek to be chic.

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:26.156
I don't know what the means.

00:32:26.156 --> 00:32:27.070
It's chic to be geek.

00:32:27.070 --> 00:32:28.945
And so, who is more
relevant than the guy who

00:32:28.945 --> 00:32:32.670
created the geekiest game of
all time, Dungeons and Dragons.

00:32:32.670 --> 00:32:35.400
And honestly, I've been
thinking a lot about this.

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:37.480
Why is it cool to be geeky now?

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:39.260
What does that even mean?

00:32:39.260 --> 00:32:41.270
And for me, geekiness,
all it means,

00:32:41.270 --> 00:32:44.080
is it's unadulterated,
unencumbered enthusiasm

00:32:44.080 --> 00:32:45.657
for something.

00:32:45.657 --> 00:32:47.240
And it's funny because
when I grew up,

00:32:47.240 --> 00:32:48.512
it wasn't cool to be a geek.

00:32:48.512 --> 00:32:50.220
I mean, I guess that
goes without saying.

00:32:50.220 --> 00:32:52.810
But it wasn't cool to be
really into something, right.

00:32:52.810 --> 00:32:55.940
It was cool to pretend like
you didn't care and to not try.

00:32:55.940 --> 00:32:59.190
That was the cool thing to do
in the '80s and '90s, right.

00:32:59.190 --> 00:33:02.604
But so why is it
chic to be geek now?

00:33:02.604 --> 00:33:04.520
To, really kind of,
really focus on something.

00:33:04.520 --> 00:33:06.228
People can be geeky
about anything today,

00:33:06.228 --> 00:33:09.090
whether it's gardening
or pottery or whatever.

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:11.570
And so, again, I
think the answer

00:33:11.570 --> 00:33:14.120
is that it's cool to be
into things these days.

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:17.540
I think that's, kind of,
what our society demands, is

00:33:17.540 --> 00:33:20.420
that we really focus and that we
apply ourselves to do something

00:33:20.420 --> 00:33:22.120
greater than ourselves.

00:33:22.120 --> 00:33:23.870
But then, I guess, the
big question for me

00:33:23.870 --> 00:33:25.530
is, well, then why D&amp;D players?

00:33:25.530 --> 00:33:27.530
How are these people some
of the original geeks?

00:33:27.530 --> 00:33:30.460
What was it about this
game that made it, kind of,

00:33:30.460 --> 00:33:35.360
this fountain of creativity
in all these things?

00:33:35.360 --> 00:33:37.600
And I think the answer
is that the game doesn't

00:33:37.600 --> 00:33:40.390
work without a lot of
engagement and commitment.

00:33:40.390 --> 00:33:42.640
So the people that were
playing this game in the '70s,

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:44.556
you couldn't play D&amp;D--
And, in fact, the game

00:33:44.556 --> 00:33:47.480
sucks if there's something
at the table that is not

00:33:47.480 --> 00:33:48.850
committed, that is not engage.

00:33:48.850 --> 00:33:51.909
It requires that everybody
really commit to this group

00:33:51.909 --> 00:33:52.700
storytelling thing.

00:33:52.700 --> 00:33:54.840
So, I guess, what
I'm trying to say

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:57.790
is that the game lends itself
to a culture of geekdom,

00:33:57.790 --> 00:34:01.790
to a culture of unadulterated
enthusiasm for something.

00:34:01.790 --> 00:34:04.850
You have to be enthusiastic
to play the game.

00:34:04.850 --> 00:34:06.870
So, again, I wear it
as a big badge of honor

00:34:06.870 --> 00:34:09.830
that we were some of
the original geeks

00:34:09.830 --> 00:34:12.500
and this has become a
cool thing now, I guess.

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:15.389
An important thing.

00:34:15.389 --> 00:34:17.040
Yes.

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:18.706
AUDIENCE: So, on the
cover of your book,

00:34:18.706 --> 00:34:21.622
you have, sort of, a
homage to Unearthed Arcana.

00:34:21.622 --> 00:34:23.809
I was wondering,
why does that seem

00:34:23.809 --> 00:34:26.500
like one of the more
iconic books for what

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:29.674
seems like a relatively
obscure rule supplement?

00:34:29.674 --> 00:34:31.340
MICHAEL WITWER: That's
a great question.

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:34.979
I actually-- I talk about
it a little bit in the book.

00:34:34.979 --> 00:34:37.520
Unearthed Arcana, first of all,
the cover art is spectacular.

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:40.610
I think we can agree that--
yeah, the original Jeff Easley

00:34:40.610 --> 00:34:41.159
cover art.

00:34:41.159 --> 00:34:43.630
So you'll notice that the
cover of my book, of course,

00:34:43.630 --> 00:34:46.719
is a referential piece
if you know that piece.

00:34:46.719 --> 00:34:50.210
It's originally a wizard
with a big tome in his castle

00:34:50.210 --> 00:34:50.790
and whatnot.

00:34:50.790 --> 00:34:52.850
And I got the same
artist, Jeff Easley,

00:34:52.850 --> 00:34:55.486
to do my cover, which is Gary,
of course, at his typewriter.

00:34:55.486 --> 00:34:56.860
Instead of the
wizard, it's Gary.

00:34:56.860 --> 00:34:58.443
It's a typewriter
instead of the book.

00:34:58.443 --> 00:35:01.840
It's in his little den and
his various effects around.

00:35:01.840 --> 00:35:04.180
And the reason that
we did that was A,

00:35:04.180 --> 00:35:05.480
it was a cool thing to do.

00:35:05.480 --> 00:35:07.021
I guess I thought
it was a neat thing

00:35:07.021 --> 00:35:08.900
to do once I got to
know Jeff Easley.

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:12.227
But Unearthed Arcana was a
particularly important book,

00:35:12.227 --> 00:35:14.560
not because it was a great
supplement, as you suggested.

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:17.310
It's kind of an
esoteric rule supplement

00:35:17.310 --> 00:35:21.860
and it's really,
kind of, aggregated

00:35:21.860 --> 00:35:24.110
pieces from the last few
years of Dragon Magazine,

00:35:24.110 --> 00:35:25.369
as some of you probably know.

00:35:25.369 --> 00:35:26.910
And they, kind of,
put them together.

00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:28.870
It was, kind of,
hastily put together.

00:35:28.870 --> 00:35:30.940
And one reason it was
is because the company

00:35:30.940 --> 00:35:32.320
was strapped at the time.

00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:34.880
When that book came
out, Gary had recently

00:35:34.880 --> 00:35:37.130
just taking control,
retaken control, of TSR.

00:35:37.130 --> 00:35:39.266
He had kicked out
his former partners

00:35:39.266 --> 00:35:41.015
and the company was
in financial shambles.

00:35:41.015 --> 00:35:42.409
It was bleeding money.

00:35:42.409 --> 00:35:43.950
They had taken on
way too many staff,

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:46.170
they had really overgrown.

00:35:46.170 --> 00:35:48.590
And so, that company--
that book, I should say,

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:52.130
was an important part in getting
that company back on track.

00:35:52.130 --> 00:35:53.810
When they released
that book, I think

00:35:53.810 --> 00:35:56.480
it sold 80,000 copies
in its first month.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:35:58.460
It was a huge success
and it was actually

00:35:58.460 --> 00:36:00.835
one of the first steps to
really getting the company back

00:36:00.835 --> 00:36:01.890
to financial solvency.

00:36:01.890 --> 00:36:04.187
So really, the story behind
the story in that case,

00:36:04.187 --> 00:36:05.270
was particularly relevant.

00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:08.165
And knowing Gary's contribution
to that book and his driving

00:36:08.165 --> 00:36:10.850
behind that book, it
actually became, kind of,

00:36:10.850 --> 00:36:13.290
symbolic for the book itself.

00:36:13.290 --> 00:36:16.945
This struggle that
Gary's going through.

00:36:16.945 --> 00:36:18.800
Other questions?

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:19.546
Yes, sir.

00:36:19.546 --> 00:36:22.315
AUDIENCE: Why is Gary Gygax
famous and Dave Arneson isn't?

00:36:22.315 --> 00:36:23.940
MICHAEL WITWER: That's
a good question.

00:36:23.940 --> 00:36:26.390
And that's-- well, they're
all good questions--

00:36:26.390 --> 00:36:27.140
and you know what?

00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:30.270
It's a very fair question
because Dave Arneson probably

00:36:30.270 --> 00:36:32.124
should be as famous
as Gary Gygax.

00:36:32.124 --> 00:36:33.165
Dave Arneson, absolutely.

00:36:35.710 --> 00:36:36.630
Oh, thank you.

00:36:36.630 --> 00:36:37.370
Yes.

00:36:37.370 --> 00:36:41.600
The question was why is Gary
Gygax famous and Dave Arneson

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:42.740
not?

00:36:42.740 --> 00:36:44.970
And it's a great question
because Dave Arneson

00:36:44.970 --> 00:36:48.470
is the co-creator of
Dungeons and Dragons.

00:36:48.470 --> 00:36:51.910
I would say there's probably
some pretty good reasons

00:36:51.910 --> 00:36:53.810
for it, whether
they're fair or not.

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:56.950
Again, on record, Dave Arneson
is the co-creator of the game.

00:36:56.950 --> 00:37:00.494
Dave Arneson is the first guy
that, probably, put together

00:37:00.494 --> 00:37:02.160
some these disparate
pieces in something

00:37:02.160 --> 00:37:04.640
that someone would recognize
as a role-playing game.

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:07.650
But he did it at the table
in a very improvised way.

00:37:07.650 --> 00:37:10.360
So wasn't, per se, written down
in a very clean sort of way.

00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:14.830
That's really happened when him
and Gary Gygax got together.

00:37:14.830 --> 00:37:17.490
What is notable is that
Dungeons and Dragons

00:37:17.490 --> 00:37:18.740
was Gary Gygax's piece.

00:37:18.740 --> 00:37:20.580
He's the one that
physically wrote it.

00:37:20.580 --> 00:37:22.500
He's the one that
physically produced it.

00:37:22.500 --> 00:37:24.560
And, as a matter of
fact, it was his company

00:37:24.560 --> 00:37:27.210
that he founded, TSR,
that produced it.

00:37:27.210 --> 00:37:29.150
And it was done at
great personal expense.

00:37:29.150 --> 00:37:31.610
He had basically
taken on two partners.

00:37:31.610 --> 00:37:33.240
Don Kaye, his
longtime best friend,

00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:36.740
who had to take out a loan
on a life insurance policy

00:37:36.740 --> 00:37:38.530
to be able to fund
his part of the game.

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:39.790
Gary had no money.

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:42.290
His own mother wouldn't
loan him money for the game.

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:45.510
And he took on a third partner,
a guy named Brian Bloom.

00:37:45.510 --> 00:37:48.760
Bloom and his family
ended up being

00:37:48.760 --> 00:37:52.650
some of the really the big--
let me put it this way.

00:37:52.650 --> 00:37:55.869
The Bloom brothers were a
very important part of TSR

00:37:55.869 --> 00:37:57.660
because they provided
a lot of the funding.

00:37:57.660 --> 00:38:01.030
These were the partners that
he ended up ousting in 1984.

00:38:01.030 --> 00:38:03.574
So things didn't go very
well with the Blooms

00:38:03.574 --> 00:38:04.240
in the long run.

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:06.365
But they were very important
to getting the company

00:38:06.365 --> 00:38:07.030
off the ground.

00:38:07.030 --> 00:38:09.340
So the answer, I think,
to the question really

00:38:09.340 --> 00:38:13.130
is that D&amp;D was a
Gary-driven product.

00:38:13.130 --> 00:38:16.030
And I mean that as a product
because it became a product

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:18.360
and he was the one that
owned it, in a essence.

00:38:18.360 --> 00:38:21.190
Arneson got a royalty on.

00:38:21.190 --> 00:38:24.775
But once Gary's company
really went up and running.

00:38:24.775 --> 00:38:26.900
And then once he did Advanced
Dungeons and Dragons,

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:29.240
which of course, is a
major revision to Dungeons

00:38:29.240 --> 00:38:30.690
and Dragons.

00:38:30.690 --> 00:38:32.180
That was a Gary Gygax product.

00:38:32.180 --> 00:38:34.430
And that became, of course,
a big point of contention.

00:38:34.430 --> 00:38:37.080
That was the reason behind the
lawsuit, as a matter of fact.

00:38:37.080 --> 00:38:39.380
So I think the main reason
is that Gary, kind of, owned

00:38:39.380 --> 00:38:39.879
the IP.

00:38:39.879 --> 00:38:42.400
He owned the company and he was
the driving force behind it.

00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:44.200
Once Arneson had
given those pieces,

00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:45.625
he was, kind of, out of it.

00:38:45.625 --> 00:38:48.000
And kind of faded into the
shadows, doing other projects,

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:49.222
important projects.

00:38:49.222 --> 00:38:50.680
But I think that's
the easy answer.

00:38:50.680 --> 00:38:55.822
Is that Gary was the front,
the face of TSR, if you will.

